[normal]AFS0059[bold]Written evidence submitted by Victoria Jaquiss[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This would be alm
[normal]ost laughable if it weren’t so serious. The main problem is that schools have been incorrectly identified as the culprits in the disadvantage that children from areas of disadvantage suffer. And the one main saviour in the sorry state of these children’s l
[normal]ives: their local school, with their familiar and experienced teacher
[normal]s – this actual saviour has
[normal] been accused and even found guilty of neglect and incompetence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I have attended nearly all
[normal] [bold]the Leeds consultation meetings for academisation. And the process in every case was, in my opinion, corrupt and totally lacking in academic rigour. In particular the situation at South Leeds 
[normal]High 
[normal]School was one of the most dishonest
[normal]. This newly made school had only just 
[normal]recovered from the merger of two very different schools [Merlyn Rees - very white ex-working class, and Matthew Murray, largely Asian], enduring at first some racial tensions
[normal]. 
[normal]After some rocky early 
[normal]moments, the Ofsted team in 200
[normal]8
[normal] [ish]
[normal] said progress was being and that the last thing this school 
[normal]needed 
[normal]was any more change and in particular to be made into an academy. 
